<topic id="d1e59"><title>Exercise 2.6</title><body><p>
<b>Derive the relations between these functions by using similar triangles.</b>
</p><p>
Solution:
</p><p>
By similar triangles, the ratio of BD to BO, 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 to 1 is the same as the ratio of CB to OC, 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>tan</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 to 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sec</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
, and of OB to AO (1 to 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>csc</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 ), and of CO to AC ( 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>s</m:mi><m:mi>e</m:mi><m:mi>c</m:mi><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 to ( 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>tan</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>cot</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 )), and of CD to BC (( 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sec</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 ) to 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>tan</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 ), and of OE to BO ( 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 to 1)
</p><p>
This tells us
</p><equation-block>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>csc</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</equation-block><p>
so that on taking complements we have as well,
</p><equation-block>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sec</m:mi><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</equation-block><p>
We also get
</p><equation-block>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>tan</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mi>sec</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</equation-block><p>
and the complementary result
</p><equation-block>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>cot</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>θ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</equation-block></body></topic>